The Connecticut Light and Power Company Wholesale Distribution Tariff
Wholesale Distribution Tariff Preamble: This Wholesale Distribution Tariff (WDT or Tariff) sets forth the rates, terms, and conditions for the provision of Wholesale Distribution Service (WDS) by The Connecticut Light and Power Company (CL&P or Owner) to customers owning or operating eligible Energy Storage Systems (ESS) interconnected to the Owners Distribution System (Customer or Customers). CL&P will deliver energy to a Customers Wholesale Charging Load under this Tariff and the Customers Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement. Owner and Customer may be referred to individually as Party or collectively as Parties. 1. Definitions 1.1 Customer. The entity taking WDS under this Tariff. 1.2 Distribution System. The electric facilities of the Owner classified as local distribution under FERCs Order No. 888 seven-factor test. 1.3 Eversource Creditworthiness Procedures: The Owners Creditworthiness Procedures contained in the ISO Tariff, ES Schedule 21, Attachment ES-L (Part A), as may be amended from time to time. 1.4 Energy Storage System. A facility that is capable of absorbing electric energy, storing it for a period of time, and thereafter dispatching the electric energy to participate in the ISO markets in accordance with ISO Tariff, Section III, Market Rule 1. 1.5 FERC. The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 1.6 Force Majeure. Any act of God, labor disturbance, act of the public enemy or terrorists, war, invasion, insurrection, riot, fire, storm or flood, ice, explosion, breakage or accident to machinery or equipment, any curtailment, order, regulation or restriction imposed by governmental military or lawfully established civilian authorities, or any other cause beyond a Partys control, including without limitation, any action or inaction by the other Party. 1.7 Good Utility Practice. Good Utility Practice shall mean any of the practices, methods, and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, including, if applicable, NERC and NPCC standards, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather includes all acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region. 1.8 IA. Interconnection Agreement. The state-jurisdictional generator Interconnection Agreement to which the Customer will be subject in order to interconnect its ESS to the Distribution System. 1.9 ISO. The ISO New England Inc., the regional transmission organization for New England. 1.10 ISO Tariff. The ISO New England Inc.s Transmission, Markets and Services Tariff and accompanying schedules and attachments, as modified and amended from time to time. 1.11 Monthly WDS Charge. The amount billed to the Customer for WDS in a billing month. 1.12 NERC. The North American Electric Reliability Corporation. 1.13 NPCC. The Northeast Power Coordinating Council, Inc. 1.14 Operational Parameters. Those parameters set forth in the IA that identify any limitations on the operations of the ESS. 1.15 Secondary Distribution System. Distribution Facilities classified by the Owner as secondary distribution facilities (pursuant to its distribution standards). 1.16 Station Service Load. All energy used for purposes other than for supporting a resale of energy back into wholesale markets. Station Service Load includes, among other things energy used for IT information technology and communications, lighting, ventilation, and safety. Efficiency losses does not constitute Station Service Load. Elements essential to battery operation namely the battery management system and thermal regulation are wholesale loads, not Station Service Load. 1.17 Wholesale Charging Load. The wholesale energy used by the Customers ESS that such that it can discharge to sell energy, capacity, ancillary services, or other FERC-jurisdictional services in the ISO marketplace as described in the ISO Tariff, Section III, Market Rule 1. 1.18 Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement (WDSA). The agreement between Owner and Customer for the provision of WDS under this Tariff and any amendments or supplements thereto. A pro forma WDSA is included with this Tariff as Attachment A. A Customer may ask for the WDSA to be filed unexecuted at FERC. 1.19 Wholesale Distribution Service. Transportation of wholesale electric power over Owners Distribution System to Customers Wholesale Charging Load. 2. Eligibility and Limitations on Scope of Service 2.1 The Owner will provide WDS under this WDT to an ESS who: (i) is a party to an IA with the Owner; (ii) requires the use of Owners Distribution System to deliver energy to its Wholesale Charging Load; (iii) participates in the wholesale market to sell energy, capacity, ancillary services or other FERC-jurisdictional services; (iv) is registered (directly or indirectly) with ISO to participate in its markets (Proof of ISO registration should be provided prior to actual service commencing); (v) has no on-site end-use load other than separately-metered Station Service Load; and (vi) is a stand-alone resource, which includes a co-located ESS (located behind a point of common coupling with another resource), if the co-located ESS is co-located with a resource that is a separately registered with the ISO, such that netting of energy between the co-located resources is prohibited. 2.1.1 WDS also is available under this WDT, if condition(s) (v) and/or (vi) is/are not met, but the Owner is satisfied that Wholesale Charging Load can never serve end-use load, other than pursuant to Section 5.2. 2.2 The Customer shall, at all times that it takes service under this Tariff and the WDSA, at its own expense, be responsible for (i) purchasing the wholesale energy being distributed to the Wholesale Charging Load, including allowances for losses; (ii) arranging for transmission and ancillary services, if required by the ISO Tariff, for the delivery of said energy to the Owners Distribution System; and (iii) arranging for state-jurisdictional retail service to serve its Station Service Load. 3. Obtaining WDS and Relationship to Generator Interconnection Study Process 3.1 At the time it submits a generator interconnection request, pursuant to applicable generator interconnection guidelines, Customer will inform Owner that it is also seeking WDS and provide relevant information to allow for necessary interconnection studies to be performed. 3.2 If an ESS has already started the interconnection process, but is not yet interconnected, when this WDT becomes effective, it may inform the Owner of its intent to take WDS and provide relevant information to allow for necessary interconnection studies to be performed, to the extent not already performed. 3.3 Unless an ESS already is interconnected to the Distribution System when this WDT becomes effective, the draft WDSA will be provided at the same time as the draft IA. If a draft IA already has been provided at the time this WDT becomes effective, the Owner will use its best efforts to provide the draft WDSA within 15 days of the effective date of WDT, assuming any necessary studies have been completed. 3.4 If an ESS already is interconnected to the Distribution System when this WDT becomes effective, is eligible for service under this WDT, and is taking retail distribution service for its Wholesale Charging Load, it can request for its service to be converted to WDS and execute a WDSA. Owner will use its best efforts to convert the service within 60 days of such request, if the requirements of the Tariff have been met. 3.5 The state-jurisdictional interconnection process allows the Customer to request WDS subject to limitations on when the Customer may take WDS for its Wholesale Charging Load or to request WDS that is not subject to limitations with regard to when it may take WDS (under normal operating conditions). If a Customers IA imposes limits on when WDS is available, and a Customer seeks service without such limitations, it should submit a new application requesting to be studied for such change. 4. Rates and Charges 4.1 The Monthly WDS Charge = Monthly Demand Charge + Customer Charge. 4.2 Customer Charge = $45.17/month. 4.3 Monthly Demand Charge = TOD Demand ChargePeak + TOD Demand ChargeMidPeak + TOD Demand ChargeOff-Peak 4.3.1 TOD Demand Charges: TOD Demand ChargePeak = TOD Demand RatePeak * the maximum metered billing demand (kW) during the Peak period of the billing month TOD Demand ChargeMid-Peak = TOD Demand RateMid-Peak * the maximum metered billing demand (kW)during the Mid-Peak period of the billing month TOD Demand ChargeOff-Peak = TOD Demand RateOff-Peak * the maximum metered billing demand (kW) during the Off-Peak period of the billing month Where: TOD Demand Rates Rate ($/kW-Month) Applicable Hours TOD Demand Rate Peak $6.82 Weekdays: 1:00 p.m. 8:00 p.m. TOD Demand Rate Mid-Peak
$2.59 Weekdays: 10:00 a.m. 1:00 p.m.; 8:00 p.m. 10:00 p.m. Weekends: 1:00 p.m. 8:00 p.m. TOD Demand Rate Off-Peak
$0.27 All Other Hours Note: All times are prevailing time. Weekdays are Monday-Friday; Weekends are Saturday and Sunday. 4.4 If the Customer fails to respond to established emergency load shedding and curtailment procedures to relieve emergencies on the Distribution System and energy is delivered to its Wholesale Charging Load, the Customer shall pay, in addition to any other charges for service hereunder, a penalty charge equal to two times the Monthly Demand Charge for each occurrence in the month in which such failure to respond occurred. 4.5 If the Customers ESS is located on the Secondary Distribution System, the Owner will develop and file at FERC under Federal Power Act Section 205 a rate for the usage of the Secondary Distribution System. 5. Metering 5.1 The Customer shall meter Wholesale Charging Load separately from Station Service Load for purposes of this WDT. 5.1.1 The metering arrangement must be capable of providing interval data that can be used to determine the maximum (hourly) demand for Wholesale Charging Load in a manner that can be processed through the Companys standard billing systems. 5.1.2 Customer shall be responsible for all reasonable and necessary costs incurred by Company for the purchase, installation, operation, maintenance, testing, repair and replacement of metering and data acquisition equipment under its IA and retail tariff. Customer shall be responsible for reasonable and necessary costs incurred by Company for meter reading and billing under this Tariff through the Customer Charge. 5.1.3 Metering requirements for Station Service Load, and, if permitted under Section 2.1.1, any other end-use load, is set forth in the applicable retail tariff. 5.2 In addition to metering to allow for the Owners measurement of Wholesale Charging Load and Station Service Load, the ESS will be subject to the metering provisions of the ISO Tariff for purposes of settling ISO-administered rates and charges. 5.3 Meter Data Access. If Owner does not own or control the meters used for billing purposes under this Agreement, Customer shall provide Owner with meter data in the form requested by Owner that is sufficient for billing purposes. If the relevant meters are owned or controlled by a third party that requires a release by Customer or permission from Customer to disclose the applicable meter data to Owner, Customer shall provide such release or grant such permission within thirty (30) days of a written request to do so. 6. Billing and Payment 6.1 Within a reasonable time after the first day of each month invoices for WDS Charges will be provided on behalf of the Owner to the Customer. The invoice shall be paid by the Customer within twenty (25) days of receipt. All payments hereunder shall be made in immediately available funds payable to the Owner, or by wire transfer to a bank named by the Owner. 6.2 Interest on any unpaid amounts (including amounts placed in escrow) shall be calculated in accordance with the methodology specified for interest on refunds in the Commissions regulations at 18 C.F.R. § 35.19a(a)(2)(iii). Interest on delinquent amounts shall be calculated from the due date of the bill to the date of payment. When payments are made by mail, bills shall be considered as having been paid on the date of receipt by the Owner. 6.3 In the event the Customer failed, for any reason other than a billing dispute as described below, to make payment to the Owner on or before the due date as described in Section 6.1 above, and such failure of payment is not corrected within thirty (30) calendar days after the Owner notifies the Customer to cure such failure, a default by the Customer shall be deemed to exist. Upon the occurrence of a default, the Owner may initiate a proceeding with FERC to terminate service but shall not terminate service until FERC so accepts any such termination request. 6.4 In the event of a billing dispute between the Owner and the Customer, the Owner will continue to provide service under this WDT as long as the Customer (i) continues to make all payments not in dispute, and (ii) pays into an independent escrow account (established in accordance with a mutually agreed upon escrow agreement) the portion of the invoice in dispute, pending resolution of such dispute. If the Customer fails to meet these two requirements for continuation of service, then the Owner may provide notice to the Customer of its intention to suspend service in sixty (60) days, in accordance with Commission policy. Upon final resolution of the dispute, in accordance with procedures set forth in Section 10 of this Agreement, if a refund is due to either Party, the Owner or the Customer, as appropriate, shall make such refund in accordance with Section 6.2 and within ten (10) business days of such resolution. 7. Nature of WDS 7.1 Owner Responsibilities. The Owner will plan, construct, operate and maintain its Distribution System in accordance with Good Utility Practice in order to provide the Customer with WDS over the Owners Distribution System to deliver energy to Wholesale Charging Load. The Owner shall include the Customers Wholesale Charging Load in its Distribution System planning and shall, consistent with Good Utility Practice, endeavor to construct and place into service sufficient Distribution System facilities to deliver the Customers power to serve its Wholesale Charging Load on a basis comparable to the Owners delivery of power to Owners retail customers, subject to the Operational Parameters, if any, set forth in the IA. 7.2 Load Shedding and Curtailment of WDS. During any period when the Owner determines that a constraint exists on all or a portion of its Distribution System, and such constraint may impair the reliability of its Distribution System, the Owner will take whatever actions, consistent with Good Utility Practice, that are reasonably necessary to maintain the reliability of the Owners Distribution System. If a constraint on the Owners Distribution System cannot be relieved through the implementation of other procedures and the Owner determines that it is necessary to curtail deliveries, the Owner shall, on a non-discriminatory basis, curtail the deliveries that effectively relieves the constraint. However, to the extent practicable and consistent with Good Utility Practice, any curtailment will be proportionately shared by the Owner and Customer. The Owner shall not direct the Customer to curtail deliveries to an extent greater than the Owner would curtail the Owners deliveries under similar circumstances. Notwithstanding the foregoing, if a portion of the Distribution System is not capable of serving all Distribution System-connected load, due to an abnormal or emergency condition, the Owner may limit WDS, to the extent operationally feasible, in order to protect human health and safety. Notwithstanding any other provisions of this Tariff, the Owner reserves the right, consistent with Good Utility Practice and on a not unduly discriminatory basis, to curtail WDS without liability on the Owners part for the purpose of making necessary adjustments to, changes in, or repairs on its lines, substations and facilities, and in cases where the continuance of WDS would endanger persons or property. In the event of any adverse condition(s) or disturbance(s) on the Owners Distribution System or on any other system(s) directly or indirectly interconnected with the Owners Distribution System, the Owner, consistent with Good Utility Practice, also may curtail WDS in order to (i) limit the extent or damage of the adverse condition(s) or disturbance(s), (ii) prevent damage to distribution facilities, or (iii) expedite restoration of service. The Owner will give the Customer as much advance notice as is practicable in the event of such curtailment. Any curtailment of WDS will not be unduly discriminatory relative to the Owners use of the Distribution System. 7.3 Scheduling of WDS Not Required. Separate schedules for WDS shall not be required under this Tariff. In transmission schedules submitted to the ISO, the Customer shall include its Wholesale Charging Load, only if required to do so under the ISO Tariff. 7.4 Conflict With ISO Tariff. If a Customer identifies a conflict between this Tariff and the ISO Tariff, the Owner and the Customer shall make good-faith efforts to resolve the conflict. 7.5 Conflicting Operating Instructions. In the event a Customer receives conflicting operating instructions from the ISO and the Owner, and, if human safety would not knowingly be jeopardized nor electric facilities subject to damage while the Customer seeks to reconcile the conflict with the appropriate ISO and Owner employees before acting, the Customer should attempt a reconciliation. Otherwise, the Customer shall adhere to the operating instructions of the Owner. Owner shall not be liable for money damages or other compensation to the Customer for issuing an operating instruction that overrides an ISO dispatch order or operating instruction unless the Owners action has been found to result from its gross negligence or willful misconduct. 8. Term. 8.1 Unless the WDSA is terminated for cause under this Tariff or as agreed to by the Parties, the WDSA will remain co-terminus with the IA. 9. Force Majeure 9.1 Neither the Owner nor the Customer will be considered in default as to any obligation under this Tariff if prevented from fulfilling the obligation due to an event of Force Majeure; provided that no event of Force Majeure affecting either Party shall excuse that Party from making payment that it is obligated to make hereunder. However, a Party whose performance under this Tariff is hindered by an event of Force Majeure shall make all reasonable efforts to perform its obligations under this Tariff, and shall promptly notify the other Party of the commencement and end of each event of Force Majeure. 10. Dispute Resolution Procedures 10.1 Internal Dispute Resolution Procedures Any dispute between a Customer and the Owner involving service under this Tariff (excluding applications for rate changes or other changes to this WDT, or to any WDSA entered into under this WDT, which shall be presented directly to FERC for resolution) shall be referred to a designated senior representative of the Owner and a senior representative of the Customer for resolution on an informal basis as promptly as practicable. In the event the designated representatives are unable to resolve the dispute within thirty (30) days by mutual agreement, such dispute may be submitted to arbitration and resolved in accordance with the arbitration procedures set forth below. 10.2 External Arbitration Procedures Any arbitration initiated under this WDT shall be conducted before a single neutral arbitrator appointed by the Parties. If the Parties fail to agree upon a single arbitrator within ten (10) days of the referral of the dispute to arbitration, each Party shall choose one arbitrator who shall sit on a threemember arbitration panel. The two arbitrators so chosen shall within twenty (20) days select a third arbitrator to chair the arbitration panel. In either case, the arbitrators shall be knowledgeable in electric utility matters, including WDS matters, and shall not have any current or past substantial business or financial relationships with any Party to the arbitration (except prior arbitration). The arbitrator(s) shall provide each of the Parties an opportunity to be heard and, except as otherwise provided herein, shall generally conduct the arbitration in accordance with the Commercial Arbitration Rules of the American Arbitration Association and any applicable Commission regulations or ISO rules. 10.3 Arbitration Decisions Unless otherwise agreed, the arbitrator(s) shall render a decision within ninety (90) days of appointment and shall notify the Parties in writing of such decision and the reasons therefore. The arbitrator(s) shall be authorized only to interpret and apply the provisions of this WDT and any WDSA entered into under this WDT and shall have no power to modify or change any of the above in any manner. The decision of the arbitrator(s) shall be final and binding upon the Parties, and judgment on the award may be entered in any court having jurisdiction. The decision of the arbitrator(s) may be appealed solely on the grounds that the conduct of the arbitrator(s), or the decision itself, violated the standards set forth in the Federal Arbitration Act and/or the Administrative Dispute Resolution Act. The final decision of the arbitrator must also be filed with FERC if it affects jurisdictional rates, terms and conditions of service or facilities. 10.4 Costs Each Party shall be responsible for its own costs incurred during the arbitration process and for the following costs, if applicable: (a) the cost of the arbitrator chosen by the Party to sit on the three-member panel and one half of the cost of the third arbitrator chosen; or (b) one half the cost of the single arbitrator jointly chosen by the Parties. 10.5 Rights Under The Federal Power Act Nothing in this section shall restrict the rights of any Party to file a complaint with FERC under relevant provisions of the Federal Power Act. 11. Limitation of Liability 11.1 The Owner shall not be liable for money damages or other compensation to the Customer for actions or omissions by the Owner in performing its obligations under this Tariff or the WDSA, except to the extent such act or omission by the Owner is found to result from its gross negligence or willful misconduct. To the extent the Customer has claims against the Owner, the Customer may only look to the assets of the Owner for the enforcement of such claims and may not seek to enforce any claims against the directors, members, shareholders, officers, employees or agents of the Owner or affiliate of either who, the Customer acknowledges and agrees, have no personal or other liability for obligations of the Owner by reason of their status as directors, members, shareholders, officers, employees or agents of the Owner or affiliate of either. 11.2 In no event shall either Party, their respective officers, directors, employees, agents, successors or assigns or their affiliates or any of their respective officers, directors, employees, agents, successors or assigns be liable to the other Party for any incidental, consequential, multiple or punitive damages, loss of revenues or profits, attorneys fees or costs arising out of, or connected in any way with performance or nonperformance of this Tariff or the WDSA. 11.3 The provisions of this Section shall survive termination, cancellation, suspension, completion or expiration of this Tariff or the WDSA. 12. Indemnification 12.1 The Customer shall at all times indemnify, defend, and save the Owner, its directors, officers, members, employees, agents, successors and assigns from any and all damages, losses, claims and liabilities by or to third parties arising out of or resulting from the performance by the Owner hereunder, any bankruptcy filings made by the Customer, or the actions or omissions of the Customer in connection with this Tariff and the WDSA, except in the case of gross negligence or willful misconduct by the Owner, its directors, officers, members, employees or agents. The amount of any indemnity payment hereunder shall be reduced (including, without limitation, retroactively) by any insurance proceeds or other amounts recovered by the indemnified party in respect of the indemnified action, claim, demand, cost, damage or liability. 13. Corporate Act and Obligation 13.1 This Tariff is the corporate act and obligation of the Customer and the Owner and shall be binding upon and shall inure to the benefit of the Parties hereto and their successors and assigns. Any claim hereunder against any stockholder, director, officer, or member of the board of either Party, in such capacity, is expressly waived. 14. Assignment 14.1 This Tariff and the WDSA shall inure to the benefit of and bind the respective successors and assigns and successors in title of the Parties hereto. No assignment by either Party of its rights and obligations hereunder shall be made or become effective without the prior written consent of the other Party in each case being obtained, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld or delayed, except that the WDSA may be assigned without such consent to an affiliate or successor of either Party, or to a person acquiring all or a controlling interest in the business assets of such Party. No assignment or transfer of rights shall relieve the assigning Party from full liability and financial responsibility for performance unless both the assignee or transferee and the other Party have so consented in writing, said consent not to be unreasonably withheld. 15. Regulatory Filings 15.1 Nothing contained in the Tariff shall be construed as affecting in any way the right of the Owner to unilaterally make application to FERC for a change in rates, terms and conditions, charges, classification of service, rule or regulation under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act and pursuant to FERC's rules and regulations promulgated thereunder. 15.2 Nothing contained in the Tariff or any Service Agreement shall be construed as affecting in any way the ability of any Customer receiving service under the Tariff to exercise its rights under the Federal Power Act and pursuant to FERC's rules and regulations promulgated thereunder. 15.3 The standard of review that shall apply in any proceeding initiated by either Party or FERC acting sua sponte which could result in a change in the rates, terms or conditions of this WDT shall be the ordinary just and reasonable standard of review, and not the higher public interest standard. Any Party that files any application under Sections 205 or 206 shall provide notice to the other Party of such filing. 16. Governing Law 16.1 Except as otherwise provided by federal law, this Tariff and the WDSA shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Connecticut. 17. Miscellaneous 17.1 Notices. Any notice, request, demand or statement required to be given by either Party to the other in connection with this WDT or a WDSA shall be given in writing and shall be sent by email (read receipt requested), registered or certified mail (return receipt requested and postage prepaid), by hand delivery, or by overnight delivery, with acknowledged receipt of delivery. Notice shall be deemed given at the date of acceptance or refusal of acceptance shown on such receipt. Any notice, request or demand pertaining to matters of an operating nature, which matters do not include requests for additional WDS or modified WDS under this WDT or the WDSA, may be served in person or by United States mail, messenger, telephone, email, or orally, as circumstances dictate, to the person designated in writing by the Party as its representative for such purposes; provided that should the same not be written, confirmation thereof shall be made in writing as soon as reasonably practicable thereafter, upon request of the Party being served. 17.2 Headings. The descriptive headings of the various sections of this Tariff have been inserted for convenience of reference only and shall in no way define, modify or restrict any of the terms and provisions thereof. 17.3 Other Instruments. From time to time after the execution of the WDSA, the Parties may execute such instruments, upon the request of the other, as may be necessary or appropriate, to carry out the intent of this Tariff and the WDSA. 17.4 Severability. Any provision of this WDT or the Customers WDSA rendered unlawful by a court of law or regulatory agency with jurisdiction will not otherwise affect the lawful obligations under this Tariff and the Customers WDSA. 17.5 Third-Party Beneficiaries. This WDT and WDSA are not intended to and shall not create rights of any character whatsoever in favor of any person, corporation, association, or entity other than the Parties, and the rights and obligations herein assumed are solely for the use and benefit of the Parties. 17.6 No Dedication. Any undertaking by one Party to the other under any provisions of this Tariff and the WDSA shall not constitute the dedication of the electric system, or any portion thereof, of any Party to the public or to the other Party, and it is understood and agreed that any such undertaking by any Party shall cease upon termination of the Agreement. 17.7 Prior Agreements: By execution of a WDSA accepting the provision of WDS under the terms and conditions set forth in this Tariff, the Parties intend for the WDT and WDSA to replace and supersede all current or prior agreements for WDS. 17.8 Entire Agreement. Subject to the preceding Paragraph, the WDT and WDSA supersede all prior agreements, discussion, communications, and correspondence for WDS between Owner and Customer, and any of their predecessors, and represent the entire understanding between Owner and Customer. 17.9 Interpretation. For the purpose of interpreting this Tariff and the WDSA, to the extent that there exists any conflict between the provisions of this Agreement and the provisions of the ISO Tariff, the provisions of this Tariff and the WDSA shall prevail. 17.10 Creditworthiness. The Owner acknowledges that the Customer is in compliance with the Eversource Creditworthiness Procedures as of the WDSA effective date. The Customer shall remain in compliance with the Eversource Creditworthiness Procedures at all times during the term of the WDSA. 17.11 Breach: Owner may terminate Customers WDSA upon breach by Customer of any material term of this WDT after ninety (90) days written notice to Customer unless Customer cures its breach within that period. If the breach is not cured in thirty (30) days after a notice of breach, the Owner may initiate a proceeding with FERC to terminate service but shall not terminate service until FERC so accepts any such termination request.

All requisite studies have been completed under the interconnection process and the Customer will be party to a co-terminus interconnection agreement (IA). 4. Customers Station Service Load and other retail load, if any, will be distinguishable from Customers Wholesale Charging Load. 5. Owner agrees to provide and Customer agrees to take and pay for WDS in accordance with the provisions of the WDT and this WDSA. Parties understand and acknowledge that the rate, terms, and conditions set forth in the WDT may be revised from time to time following appropriate submission to and acceptance by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) under the Federal Power Act. 6. All provisions of the WDT, and any subsequent revisions to the WDT approved by FERC, are hereby incorporated by reference. 7. Customer shall comply with the Eversource Creditworthiness Procedures as of the effective date. 8. As long as proof of ISO registration has been provided, service under this Agreement shall commence on the later of (l) the requested service commencement date, (2) the date on which construction of any required upgrades under the relevant IA are completed, or (3) such other date as it is permitted to become effective by FERC. Termination of service under this agreement shall be as set forth under the relevant WDT provisions or on another date mutually agreed upon by Parties. 9. WDS will be subject to Operational Parameters as defined in the Tariff and set forth in the relevant IA. 10. Any dispute arising with respect to matters under this Agreement will be resolved pursuant to the WDT. 11. Persons for Notice: For Owner (Contract)
